{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502196"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1834"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.18,0.12,0.37,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58526"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1834"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43942"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"518"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2648"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9115"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58526"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of increasing colicky abdominal pain and distension. He has become constipated and has not passed anything per rectum for the last 48 hours. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a distended, soft abdomen, apart from a tender area in the right iliac fossa. There are increased and high-pitched bowel sounds. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appendiceal mass","Appendicitis with associated abscess","Small bowel intussusception","Carcinoma of the caecum","Ileocaecal strictures secondary to Crohn\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the caecum\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of an intestinal obstruction. The CT scan shows a 6 cm mass in the region of the caecal pole (Image), with radiographic findings consistent with a caecal obstruction, including multiple air-fluid levels and increased calibre of the small intestine. This obstruction is almost certainly secondary to the mass lesion. The most likely explanation for this clinical and radiological picture is a carcinoma of the caecum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApproximately 10% of patients with colorectal cancer present with acute large bowel obstruction. The onset of symptoms can worsen over a period of several weeks, or patients (such as in this case) may present with rapidly progressive symptoms over a shorter time course (i.e. hours to days).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan does not demonstrate any obvious abnormality of the appendix, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendiceal mass\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendicitis with associated abscess\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect answer options. Furthermore, his history and examination findings are not consistent with a diagnosis of appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel intussusception\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cause of intestinal obstruction in adults and is seen more commonly in the paediatric population. There is no evidence of intussusception on the CT scan, thus making this an incorrect answer option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient reports no significant medical conditions and there is no evidence on his history of symptoms that might point towards Crohn\u0027s disease (e.g. chronic diarrhoea, fatigue, weight loss, joint pain). As such \u003Cstrong\u003Eileocaecal strictures secondary to Crohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is very unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Approximately 10% of patients with colorectal cancer present with acute large bowel obstruction."],"references":["Veld JV, Beek KJ, Consten ECJ, ter Borg F, van Westreenen HL, Bemelman WA, et al. Definition of large bowel obstruction by primary colorectal cancer: A systematic review. Colorectal Dis. 2020;23(4):787\u2013804. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8248390/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43942"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15313"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21118"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15313"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"im